Copyright (C) Robert Fennis and EMerge contributors.
Upstream: https://github.com/FennisRobert/EMerge

The following files in `crates/rapidfem-fd` and `crates/rapidfem-core`
contain code directly ported from EMerge. Per the GPL-2.0-or-later
grant, they are redistributed here under GPL-3.0-or-later with the Gmsh
additional permission carried forward.

  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/assembly.rs         (port of microwave_3d.py
                                              assemble_and_solve)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/basis.rs            (port of nedleg2.py
                                              Nedelec2Basis)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/interp.rs           (port of ned2_tet_interp.py)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/sparam.rs           (port of sparam.py)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/touchstone.rs       (port of touchstone.py)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/tri_assembly.rs     (port of robinbc.py
                                              ned2_tri_stiff / force)
  crates/rapidfem-fd/src/waveguide.rs        (port of microwave_bc.py
                                              RectangularWaveguide,
                                              CoaxPort, LumpedPort,
                                              FloquetPort,
                                              UserDefinedPort,
                                              SurfaceImpedance,
                                              LumpedElement, ABC, plus
                                              cs.py CoordinateSystem)
  crates/rapidfem-core/src/materials.rs      (port of materials.py
                                              build_material_tensors)
  crates/rapidfem-core/src/quadrature.rs     (port of quadrature tables
                                              from EMerge)

New code in `crates/rapidfem-fd/src/waveguide.rs` (the `NumericalWavePort`
class and its supporting helpers) and in `crates/rapidfem-core/src/port_eigen.rs`
(the 2-D wave-port mode eigensolver) is original to this project, also
under GPL-3.0-or-later.

The volume element assembly (`crates/rapidfem-fd/src/tet_assembly_r2.rs`)
and the barycentric integration coefficients (`coefficients.rs`) are
original, clean-room work: the canonical Nédélec first-kind order-2 element
and the simplex integration identity were re-derived from primary
mathematics (see `derivations/`), independent of EMerge. They replace the
former `tet_assembly.rs` port, which has been removed.

